    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes to TN, but frame as connection not warning",
    "content": "**Yes to a TN, but frame it as a connection, not a warning.**\n\nA philosophically literate reader encountering \"category theory\" in a philosophical text *will* think of Kant. This is not confusion -- it is a reasonable association. The TN should not say \"do not confuse these\" (patronizing, and wrong -- the overlap is intentional). It should say something like:\n\n\"The author's use of category theory (范畴论) refers to the mathematical discipline of objects and morphisms. The resonance with Kant's categories (Kategorien) -- the a priori structures by which experience is organized -- is not accidental: in this framework, the categorical structures of E play an analogous role to Kant's categories, organizing the manifold of phenomena into structured experience. The difference is that the author's structures are descriptive and emergent rather than transcendentally given.\"\n\nThis does three things: (1) disambiguates for the reader who needs it, (2) validates the Kantian association for the reader who made it, (3) positions the author's framework relative to Kant in one sentence. The Kantian expert likely has similar thoughts on this connection."
  }
}
